      <NewsComponent>
        <ContentItem>
          <MediaType FormalName="Text"/>
          <Format FormalName="bcNITF2.5"/>
          <DataContent>
            <media media-type="image" style="leftSide">
<media-reference mime-type="" data-location="#photo0" />
</media>
<p>Actor Michael Douglas and his movie-star wife, Catherine Zeta-Jones, appeared in court to testify in a hearing for a woman alleged to have stalked and threatened Zeta-Jones.</p>

            <p>The written and telephone threats "affected me and ... will affect me for the rest of my life," Zeta-Jones testified.</p>
            <p>She said when she first learned of the threats, she felt stunned and shocked. "I was trembling, I felt I needed to find out more. I was just at a loss for words," the actress said.</p>
            <p>Zeta-Jones, who won an Oscar for "Chicago" in 2002, testified in a preliminary hearing for Dawnette Knight, 32, who is accused of threatening the actress with death.</p>
            <p>Earlier, Douglas had testified that he initially did not tell his wife about the threats when he learned about them in March, because he thought "it would upset her tremendously," but relented when they became more serious.</p>
            <p>Judge Patricia Schnegg must now decide if there is sufficient evidence to put Knight on trial.</p>
          </DataContent>
        </ContentItem>
